'''Isa Soares''' (born 1953) is a Brazilian-born Argentine dancer and activist involved in creating awareness of the African traditions of Argentina and fighting racism against [[Afro-Argentines|Afro-Argentine]] peoples. She was one of the pioneers in developing [[African dance]] interpretation and instruction in Argentina.

==Early life==
María Isabel Soares Sousa was born in 1953 <!-- on 4 May 1953 --> in [[Maragogipe]], of the Brazilian state of [[Bahia]] to [[Afro-Brazilian]] parents Iraildes Sousa Gomes and Fernando Bispo Soares. Her father had degrees in both biochemistry and music, and her mother was a dressmaker and [[tobacconist]]. After completing her primary and secondary education, Soares attended the [[Federal Institute of Bahia]] in [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], earning her teaching credentials in 1972. She moved to [[São Paulo]] and had a son, while continuing her education at the [[University of São Paulo]]. The focus of her studies was on the socio-cultural and historic development of dance and the impact of the [[slave trade]] upon cultural practices.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}}

==Career==
While continuing her studies, Soares worked as a primary school teacher.{{sfn|Más|2016}} She took dance lessons with [[Wilson Silva]], who taught her the basic techniques of African dance and how those spread into the Americas through ''[[candombe]]'' in Uruguay, ''[[samba]]'' from Brazil and [[Tap dance|tap dancing]] in the United States. In 1982, she married and as was expected of women in her generation, followed her husband to Argentina, giving up her career in 1983.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}}{{sfn|Más|2016}} The couple settled in [[Bahía Blanca]] and Soares returned to her studies through the National Technical Education Council ({{lang-es|Consejo Nacional de Educación Técnica (CONET)}}), earning her technical instructor's certification. As there were few prospects for a black woman in the arts to earn a living in Bahía Blanca, she left the area in 1985 and moved to [[Buenos Aires]]. Between 1985 and 1987, Soares studied and worked as a dance instructor on a scholarship in the dance school of [[Aida Prestifilippo]], the principal dancer of the [[Teatro Colón]]. In addition to providing the scholarship Prestifilippo helped introduce Soares to the dance circuit in Buenos Aires, allowing her to perform at various local venues.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}} 

The era was one of cultural expansion, following the suppression of individual expression throughout the period of [[National Reorganization Process]] from 1973-1983.{{sfn|Florencia|2013|p=3}} From the end of the dictatorship, Soares gave lessons in African dance at a small salon on Corrientes Street in Buenos Aires and organized performances and events to expand the knowledge of black culture in Argentina.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}}{{sfn|Florencia|2013|p=3}} Beginning in 1987, she worked as a dance instructor of a course ''Dance of Orixás'' ({{lang-es|Danza de Orixás}} for the Centro Cultural Rector Ricardo Rojas, an organization affiliated with the [[University of Buenos Aires]].{{sfn|Florencia|2013|p=3}} Between 1990 and 2006, Soares was the coordinator for African dance at the Centro{{sfn|Más|2016}} and began traveling to places like [[Rosario, Santa Fe]] in the [[Santa Fe Province]] to teach and back to Brazil for students to train in Bahia.{{sfn|Florencia|2013|p=3}}{{sfn|Montenegro|2017}} She also hosted annual summer courses on dances with African roots through the Municipal Institute of Education for Art in the [[Avellaneda Partido|Municipality of Avellaneda]].{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}}{{sfn|Ministry of Education|2006}} Forming an association with activists, artists and intellectuals, Soares actively worked to fight racial discrimination and bring back an awareness of the roots of black culture in Argentina.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}}{{sfn|Montenegro|2017}}

At the end of 2006, Soares left the Center, though she continued with private dance instruction and taught a seminar which consolidated Afro-Brazilian and [[Afro-Cuban]] dance styles.{{sfn|Más|2016}} In 2007, she began teaching courses at the [[Instituto Universitario Nacional del Arte]]{{sfn|Infante|2010|p=86}} as well as directing an independent project, known as the Alábase Project, which focuses on the study and performance of the methodology of the [[Yoruba people|Yoruban]] dance based upon the tradition of ''xiré''.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}} She is considered one of the pioneering dancers who brought African cultural expression back to Argentina after the close of the dictatorship.{{sfn|Fernández Bravo|2016}}{{sfn|Plaza|2006}}

